<DOC><DOCNO> AP891017-0216 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-89 0147EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     10-17 0938</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0977</SECOND><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Wall Street averted another Black Monday and hada Blue Chip Monday instead, as some of the heaviest trading inhistory produced a rally in big-name stocks and losses in manysmaller issues.   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, benefiting from a``flight to quality,'' rose 88.12 points, or 3.4 percent, to2,657.38, erasing nearly half the losses suffered in last week'sFriday the 13th plunge.   The gain was the fourth-biggest point rise on record, althoughit did not rank among the top percentage gainers. Volume totaled416.29 million shares, also the fourth largest in history.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Stock markets around the world tumbled as foreigners reacted toWall Street's Friday plunge with a deluge of sell orders thatclogged exchanges from Tokyo to Lisbon.   But analysts said that despite sharp drops in stock pricesMonday, the global backlash was nowhere near what it was two yearsago in the wake of Wall Street's Black Monday collapse.   In Tokyo, the key 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average closed down647.33 points, or 1.8 percent, at 34,468.69. London's FinancialTimes-Stock Exchange 100-stock index was down by more than 9percent at one point but finished at its high of the day, off 70.5points, or 3.2 percent, at 2,163.40.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Bush provided reassuring words in aneffort to calm gyrating financial markets while the Federal Reservebacked up the words with $2 billion in cash poured into the U.S.banking system.   The Fed's supply of cash was viewed as a sizable effort on thepart of the central bank to contain the Friday the 13th stockmarket plunge and make sure it did not have disastrous rippleeffects through the rest of the economy.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Bush administration conferred closely withforeign allies, the Federal Reserve Board and Wall Street officialsthrough the weekend in mapping a strategy for averting a ``BlackMonday'' crisis that, in the end, never developed, sources said.   Within the first hour of trading Monday on the New York StockExchange, President Bush pointedly told reporters, ``I'm notworried.'' Behind the business-as-usual image, however, the sourcessaid, was a weekend of intensive private consultations intended toforestall an escalation of Friday's 190-point drop in the Dow JonesIndustrial Average.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Donald Trump scrapped his proposed $7 billionoffer for AMR Corp. but said he was still considering making alower bid for the parent of American Airlines.   Trump said Monday he was withdrawing his offer because of themarket volatility and its effect on AMR's stock. But he said he wasalso considering increasing his holdings in AMR or selling hisstock.</TEXT><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   UAL Corp. stock plunged as the market followedthe lead of key banks that rejected financing for a $6.75 billioncash buyout offer made for the parent of United Airlines by amanagement-pilot group.   Analysts differed Monday on whether the sharp fall in UAL stockprices meant the death of a deal that collapsed Friday when thebuyout group announced it could not obtain financing for its$300-a-share offer.   Parties to the buyout said Monday that all sides were working torestructure the offer. UAL stock plunged Monday nearly $60 a shareto close at $219.34.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, in apitch for strong capital standards, told bankers at their annualconvention that banks like many other corporations today are highlyleveraged.   Greenspan, addressing the American Bankers Association, onMonday cited recent efforts by banks to build their capital, thecushion that protects government insurance funds and by extensionthe taxpayers from losses.   But, he added, ``despite the progress many of you have made inrecent years ... capital levels for the industry remain at the lowend of their broad historical range.''</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Business sales far outpaced inventoryaccumulation in August, the government said in a report thatsuggested unsold goods aren't piling up and the economy is infairly strong shape.   The Commerce Department said inventories edged up 0.3 percent toa seasonally adjusted $789.9 billion while sales advanced a steep3.1 percent to $526.8 billion. The pace in inventories was downfrom a 0.9 percent hike in July while sales rose from a 0.9 declinethe previous month.</TEXT><DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Striking Boeing Co. workers welcomed news thatcontract talks with the company would resume Wednesday, butwondered whether the aerospace giant would offer anything new.   Boeing and the Machinists union were told Monday a meeting wouldbe held Wednesday in the offices of federal mediator DouglasHammond, two weeks after 57,800 workers walked off the job.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Blue-chip stocks bounded ahead Monday after a sharp wave ofearly selling but prices of many other stocks trailed behind. TheDow Jones average of 30 industrials, knocked down by a powerfulselling wave in the opening minutes of trading, later rallied 88.12points to close at 2,657.38.   The dollar finished mixed in hectic U.S. trading but above itsclosing levels earlier in the day on overseas markets.   Treasury bonds returned most of their gains from the year'sbiggest rally last week as investors cashed in on a previous moveto safer fixed-income investments.   Stock-index futures prices soared on the Chicago MercantileExchange, erasing some investor fears and more than half of lastFriday's losses while easing jitters on other commodity markets.Copper futures fell sharply while precious metals gained; grainsand soybeans rallied; livestock and meat futures retreated andenergy futures sagged.</TEXT></DOC>